          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "Collaborative Learning",
          "Knowledge-Based + Hybrid",
          "Collaborative Activities",
          "80 undergraduate Computer Science students (University of West Attica, Greece)",
          "Java Programming Course",
          "Questionnaire (Gardner & Korth Collaborative Learning Styles), \nExpert-Defined Weights from 14 instructors",
          "Learners complete a collaborative learning style questionnaire (Gardner & Korth, 1998), which classifies them into four styles: Accommodator, Converger, Diverger, Assimilator. Initial weights per style and per activity are defined by experts and fed to the ANN.",
          "Static once per learner profile (no continuous updates). System generates new recommendations per learner instance but does not adapt dynamically.",
          "Weights defined by experts are normalized and fed to the ANN as input nodes. WSM (Weighted Sum Model) acts as the activation function, producing an output vector representing the percentage likelihood of participation in each collaborative activity type.",
          "Top-N collaborative activities",
          "{Satisfaction on Assignment: 8.55/10 vs 6.625/10, Grades: 7.825/10 vs 6.25/10}",
          "Combines Artificial Neural Networks (ANN) with the Weighted Sum Model (WSM) for multi-criteria decision-making, based on learners’ collaborative styles.Model outputs participation percentages per activity type → used for recommendations and grouping.\n\nEmpirical evaluation shows significant improvement in satisfaction and learning outcomes.Extends adaptive CSCL personalization by incorporating group-level learning style intelligence.",
          "Recommendations are static, not adaptive to ongoing learner behavior.\n\nLearning style detection depends entirely on self-reported questionnaire data.\n\nExpert weighting introduces subjectivity.\n\nEvaluation limited to a single course and small population.\n\nNo long-term validation or group interaction analysis beyond the Java course."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
